<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv"></span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p1"></span> <span class="c4"><span
id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p1.1"></span>Canon LXXXIII.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p2"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p2.1"></span>No</span> one may give the Eucharist to
the bodies of the dead; for it is written “Take and eat.”  But the
bodies of the dead can neither “take” nor “eat.”

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p3"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p3.1"></span>Notes.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p4"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p4.1"></span>Ancient Epitome of Canon LXXXIII.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p5"></span>The Sacraments must not be given to
a dead body.

<span id="xiv.iii.lxxxiv-p6"></span>This is canon iv. of the Council of
Hippo, in the year 393.  (*Vide* Hefele, Vol. II., p. 397.)  The earlier
canon includes baptism also, in its prohibition.  This is canons xviii.
and xx. of the African code, according to the Greek numbering.

